If you do not have to validate the string for only digits you may use

    s.replace(/(?:^0)?.{2}(?!$)/g, &#39;$&amp; &#39;)

See the [regex demo][1]. 

**Details**

 - `(?:^0)?` - an optional occurrence of `0` at the start of the string
 - `.{2}` - any 2 chars other than line break chars
 - `(?!$)` - not at the end of the string.

The `$&amp;` in the replacement string is the whole match backreference.

If you need to check the string first, do it with `if (/^\d+$/.test(str)) {...}` and then apply this regex. 

JS demo:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var strs = [&#39;1234568790&#39;, &#39;012345&#39;, &#39;0000000&#39;];
    for (var i = 0; i &lt; strs.length; i++) {
      console.log(strs[i].replace(/(?:^0)?\d{2}(?!$)/g, &#39;$&amp; &#39;));
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

  [1]: https://regex101.com/r/p1ltVX/2

You could just include an alternative check if the string starts with zero to split after the first 3 digits and otherwise split on 2 digits.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let s = &#39;01234568790&#39;;
    s = s.replace(/\s/g, &#39;&#39;).replace(/(^0\d{2}|\d{2})/g, &#39;$1 &#39;);
    console.log(s);
    // 012 34 56 87 90

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

